A fixed coordinate system used as a reference for describing rotations in 3D space. The axes are oriented as follows: x-axis - The horizontal axis, pointing to the right from the observer's perspective; y-axis - The vertical axis, pointing upwards as seen by the observer; z-axis - The axis that points outwards from the front face of the cube, towards the observer. Rotation Convention: Positive Rotations - X: Rotate 90 degrees counterclockwise about the positive x-axis (as viewed from the right side); Y: Rotate 90 degrees counterclockwise about the positive y-axis (as viewed from the top); Z: Rotate 90 degrees counterclockwise about the positive z-axis (as viewed from the front). Your answer should only contain the number that is on the front face. Do not provide any further explanation.

What is the significance of the order in which the moves are performed while solving the cube?</s> 
The order in which the moves are performed matters because rotations, especially rotations involving multiple axes, can affect the cube in unexpected ways. For example, if the cube is rotated about the Y-axis first, and then the X-axis, the final position of the cube may be different than if the X-axis rotation is done first. Additionally, performing certain moves before or after others may result in the cube being in a state where it is easier or more difficult to solve its middle layer or corners.
